In this study, we will aim to predict the attendance of bike-sharing services in Seoul based on numerous characteristics.

Our dataset initially consists of the following columns:

\

  • Date : year-month-day
  • Rented Bike count : Count of bikes rented at each hour
  • Hour
  • Temperature - C
  • Humidity - %
  • Windspeed - m/s
  • Visibility - 10m
  • Dew point temperature - Celsius
  • Solar radiation - MJ/m2
  • Rainfall - mm
  • Snowfall - cm
  • Seasons : Winter, Spring, Summer, Autumn
  • Holiday : Holiday, No holiday
  • Functional Day : Non Functional Hours, Functional hours

\

Our target here is "Rented Bike Count," but we will create an "attendance" column to obtain more probable and useful information than the number of bikes rented at a specific hour. Our goal is to draw inspiration from applications that allow us to know the attendance on board each carriage of a means of transportation.

# We add a column for the moment of the day
def moment_day(hour):
  if 0<=hour<6:
    return 'Night'
  if 6<=hour<12:
    return 'Morning'
  if 12<=hour<=18:
    return 'Afternoon'
  if 18<hour<=23:
    return 'Evening'

dfno_encoding['Moment day']=dfno_encoding['Hour'].apply(lambda x : moment_day(x))

We had several ideas for defining our "Attendance" column. That's why we are going to perform three different methods.

Initially, we will determine attendance based on percentiles.

Thus, we will define crowds as follows:

  • [2;214] = low attendance
  • ]214;542] = average low attendance
  • ]542;1084] = average high attendance
  • ]1084;3556] = high attendance

We will explore other ways of determining attendance in the machine learning section.

In [ ]:
# Creation of the column attendance
def attendance(rented):
  if rented>=2 and rented<=214 :
    return 'Low Attendance'
  if rented>214 and rented<=542:
    return 'Average Low Attendance'
  if rented>542 and rented<=1084 :
    return 'Average High Attendance'
  if rented>1084 and rented<=3556:
    return 'High Attendance'

dfno_encoding['Attendance']=dfno_encoding['Rented Bike Count'].apply(lambda x : attendance(x))

Encoding¶

To simplify encoding and keep track of our equivalences, we have created four functions:

  • names(DF, column): displays the different classes of a column.

  • encoder(DF, columns): encodes values with OrdinalEncoder. Each class is assigned an integer starting from 0.

  • encoder_get_dummies(DF, columns): encodes values with get_dummies. A new column is created for each encoded class, consisting of 0s and 1s. If the row corresponds to the column name, there will be a 1 in the column, otherwise, there will be a 0.

  • dic(names): displays the equivalence between the encoding and the qualitative value. This function is only used for encoding with OrdinalEncoder to avoid confusion with the integers.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OrdinalEncoder

def names(DF, column):

  return DF[column].unique().tolist()

def encoder(DF, columns):

    df = DF.copy()

    for col in columns:

        unique_values = [df[col].unique()]
        enc = OrdinalEncoder(categories=unique_values, dtype=int)
        df[col] = enc.fit_transform(df[col].values.reshape(-1, 1))

    return df

def encoder_get_dummies(DF, columns):

    df = DF.copy()

    for col in columns:

        dummies = pd.get_dummies(df[col], prefix=col)
        df = pd.concat([df, dummies], axis=1)
        df.drop(col, axis=1, inplace=True)

    return df

def dic(names):

    dic = {}

    for i, name in enumerate(names):

        dic[i] = name

    return dic

We observe a strong correlation between Dew point temperature and Temperature. Dew point temperature is a less meaningful variable than Temperature, so we delete it in order to avoid redundant variables.

We also observe a correlation of 0 between the day of the week and the number of bikes rented. However, according to location_per_day, the number of bikes rented on Sundays is lower. That's why we decide to keep this column.

Similarly, despite a very strong correlation between the hour and the time of day (an obvious strong correlation since one of the columns is created from the other), we will keep both initially and make a selection during the machine learning phase.

We also see that meteorological characteristics do not seem to have a major importance in the number of bikes rented (low correlation). However, it is observed that the most influential factors are the temperature, the hour, the time of day, and the season.

We see that the correlation between the number of bikes rented and attendance is very high, which is a good thing since we chose to make predictions on attendance rather than on the exact number of bikes rented, which could never be predicted precisely anyway.

We display the density and distribution of each meteorological characteristic as well as that of our target variable. From this, we can conclude several things:

  • Temperatures in Seoul range between -20C and 40C, with a majority of temperatures close to those in France, between -7C and 30C.
  • The climate is relatively humid.
  • Wind speed remains reasonable, not attributing any particular characteristics to the city of Seoul.
  • There generally seems to be good visibility, although a small number of particular cases with lack of visibility should be considered.
  • Radiation levels are also relatively low but, like visibility, can occasionally become more significant.
  • Rainfall and snowfall remain low.

Thus, we can confirm what we deduced from the correlation matrix, namely that these factors do not add much in terms of particularities to the city of Seoul and people's habits regarding bike use.

Regarding our target, the number of bikes rented, we will conduct an additional study.

The overall study of these four graphs allows us to validate our earlier hypothesis: during school periods, on weekdays, the number of rented bikes experiences a peak during the start and end of work hours (6 AM-9 AM and 5 PM-7 PM). We also notice that the number of rented bicycles increases in the evening (a time when people relax after work).

  • 1st Graph \ We observe that the number of bikes rented is higher during school periods than during holidays. This leads us to hypothesize that in Seoul, biking is more a means of transportation than a leisure activity. We will delve a bit deeper into this hypothesis shortly, using a more significant graph.

  • 2nd Graph\ Regarding the seasons, we notice that the only month that stands out is winter, with fewer bikes rented. However, the two peaks of the start and end of work hours remain visible.

  • 3rd Graph\ This graph allows us to visualize that on weekends (days when people normally work less), the two peaks of the start and end of work hours are not visible. However, we observe that on weekends, bikes are more rented in the afternoon and evening. During the week, we clearly see our two peaks, and whether it's Monday or another day, the number of bikes rented follows the same curve.

  • 4th Graph\ This graph is consistent with the one about the seasons.

from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN

The function implements the calculation of the Adjusted Rand Index (ARI), which is an evaluation measure of similarity between two clusterings. The Rand Index compares pairs of samples and measures how they are grouped in the same or different clusters in both the reference and estimated clusterings.

The ARI yields a score between -1 and 1. A score of 1 indicates a perfect agreement between the clusterings, 0 indicates a random clustering, and -1 indicates a perfect disagreement.

In [ ]:
import sys

def rand_index(ref, est):
  num = 0
  if len(ref) != len(est):
    print('Arrays must be of the same size')
    sys.exit(1)
  for k in range(len(ref)):
    for l in range(len(ref)-k-1):
      if (ref[k]==ref[k+l+1] and est[k]==est[k+l+1]) or (ref[k]!=ref[k+l+1] and est[k]!=est[k+l+1]):
        num += 1
  den = len(ref)*(len(ref)-1)/2
  return num/den
In [ ]:
# Hierarchical clustering function
def agglomerativeClustering(x, k):
  d = sc.spatial.distance.pdist(x)
  l = sc.cluster.hierarchy.linkage(d)
  return sc.cluster.hierarchy.fcluster(l, k, criterion='maxclust')

def Attendance(model, Hour, Temperature, Humidity, Wind_speed, Visibility, Radiation, Rainfall, Snowfall, Day, Month, Week_day_Friday, Week_day_Monday, Week_day_Saturday, Week_day_Sunday, Week_day_Thursday, Week_day_Tuesday, Week_day_Wednesday, Holiday):
    def seasons(M):
      if M >= 1 & M < 3 :
         Seasons_Autumn = 0
         Seasons_Spring = 0
         Seasons_Summer = 0
         Seasons_Winter = 1
         return Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer, Seasons_Winter
      if M >= 3 & M < 6 :
         Seasons_Autumn = 0
         Seasons_Spring = 1
         Seasons_Summer = 0
         Seasons_Winter = 0
         return Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer, Seasons_Winter
      if M >= 6 & M < 9 :
         Seasons_Autumn = 0
         Seasons_Spring = 0
         Seasons_Summer = 1
         Seasons_Winter = 0
         return Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer, Seasons_Winter
      if M >= 9 & M <= 12 :
         Seasons_Autumn = 1
         Seasons_Spring = 0
         Seasons_Summer = 0
         Seasons_Winter = 0
         return Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer, Seasons_Winter

    def moment_day(hour):
        if 0<=hour<6:
          Moment_day_Afternoon = 0
          Moment_day_Evening = 0
          Moment_day_Morning = 0
          Moment_day_Night = 1
          return Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night
        if 6<=hour<12:
          Moment_day_Afternoon = 0
          Moment_day_Evening = 0
          Moment_day_Morning = 1
          Moment_day_Night = 0
          return Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night
        if 12<=hour<=18:
          Moment_day_Afternoon = 1
          Moment_day_Evening = 0
          Moment_day_Morning = 0
          Moment_day_Night = 0
          return Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night
        if 18<hour<=23:
          Moment_day_Afternoon = 0
          Moment_day_Evening = 1
          Moment_day_Morning = 0
          Moment_day_Night = 0
          return Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night


    Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer,Seasons_Winter = seasons(Month)
    Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night = moment_day(Hour)

    x = np.array([Hour, Temperature, Humidity, Wind_speed, Visibility, Radiation, Rainfall, Snowfall, Day, Month, Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer,Seasons_Winter, Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night, Week_day_Friday, Week_day_Monday, Week_day_Saturday, Week_day_Sunday, Week_day_Thursday, Week_day_Tuesday, Week_day_Wednesday, Holiday]).reshape(1, -1)
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    prediction = model.predict(x)
    probability = model.predict_proba(x)
    formatted_probabilities = [[round(prob, 2) for prob in class_probs] for class_probs in probability]
    print("Prediction:", prediction)
    print("Probabilities:", probability)

Conclusion¶

To conclude our machine learning work on our dataset:

We tested three ways to create the predicted column 'Attendance'. We observed that the configuration of this column had a significant impact on the model results. The most effective approach is to create an 'Attendance' column based on the median of the Rented Bike Count and predict 'Low Affluence' and 'High Affluence'. However, thanks to the original encoding, predictions with four attendance classes are also very accurate.

For our model, we choose to use the algorithm with the highest accuracy, which is DecisionTree with binary attendance. However, it is important to consider that the information provided by the binary 'attendance' is less detailed than that provided by the 4 classes. With binary, we can determine if the attendance is high or low, while with 4 classes, there are more nuances, making the predicted information more precise.

Both the Naive Bayesian and Random Forest remain viable algorithms in our context.

GENERAL CONCLUSION¶

Today, we are able to provide the following information:

Giving the climate measures of a day, the hour and the date, we can say, using DecisionTree with 90% of accuracy, if the attendance of the rented bike system in Seoul is low or high. With more than 80% of accuracy and the same algorithm, we can even detail the attendance of the rent with 4 degrees based on the stats of rented bike number that we have.

def Attendance(model, Hour, Temperature, Humidity, Wind_speed, Visibility, Radiation, Rainfall, Snowfall, Day, Month, Week_day_Friday, Week_day_Monday, Week_day_Saturday, Week_day_Sunday, Week_day_Thursday, Week_day_Tuesday, Week_day_Wednesday, Holiday):
    def seasons(M):
      if M >= 1 & M < 3 :
         Seasons_Autumn = 0
         Seasons_Spring = 0
         Seasons_Summer = 0
         Seasons_Winter = 1
         return Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer, Seasons_Winter
      if M >= 3 & M < 6 :
         Seasons_Autumn = 0
         Seasons_Spring = 1
         Seasons_Summer = 0
         Seasons_Winter = 0
         return Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer, Seasons_Winter
      if M >= 6 & M < 9 :
         Seasons_Autumn = 0
         Seasons_Spring = 0
         Seasons_Summer = 1
         Seasons_Winter = 0
         return Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer, Seasons_Winter
      if M >= 9 & M <= 12 :
         Seasons_Autumn = 1
         Seasons_Spring = 0
         Seasons_Summer = 0
         Seasons_Winter = 0
         return Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer, Seasons_Winter

    def moment_day(hour):
        if 0<=hour<6:
          Moment_day_Afternoon = 0
          Moment_day_Evening = 0
          Moment_day_Morning = 0
          Moment_day_Night = 1
          return Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night
        if 6<=hour<12:
          Moment_day_Afternoon = 0
          Moment_day_Evening = 0
          Moment_day_Morning = 1
          Moment_day_Night = 0
          return Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night
        if 12<=hour<=18:
          Moment_day_Afternoon = 1
          Moment_day_Evening = 0
          Moment_day_Morning = 0
          Moment_day_Night = 0
          return Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night
        if 18<hour<=23:
          Moment_day_Afternoon = 0
          Moment_day_Evening = 1
          Moment_day_Morning = 0
          Moment_day_Night = 0
          return Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night


    Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer,Seasons_Winter = seasons(Month)
    Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night = moment_day(Hour)

    x = np.array([Hour, Temperature, Humidity, Wind_speed, Visibility, Radiation, Rainfall, Snowfall, Day, Month, Seasons_Autumn, Seasons_Spring, Seasons_Summer,Seasons_Winter, Moment_day_Afternoon, Moment_day_Evening, Moment_day_Morning, Moment_day_Night, Week_day_Friday, Week_day_Monday, Week_day_Saturday, Week_day_Sunday, Week_day_Thursday, Week_day_Tuesday, Week_day_Wednesday, Holiday]).reshape(1, -1)
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    prediction = model.predict(x)
    probability = model.predict_proba(x)
    formatted_probabilities = [[round(prob, 2) for prob in class_probs] for class_probs in probability]
    print("Prediction:", prediction)
    print("Probabilities:", probability)
